{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16003"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16003"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.12,0.15,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86419"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70698"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"521"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"3880"},{"type":"tags","id":"8066"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8142"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86419"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is referred to a breast surgeon following an abnormal screening mammogram. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The mammogram shows clustered microcalcifications measuring 1 cm in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no palpable mass, skin changes, or nipple discharge. The axillary examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound examination shows no discrete mass. Vacuum-assisted biopsy of the microcalcifications reveals ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS), intermediate grade, without invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tamoxifen alone","Core needle biopsy","Mammographic surveillance","Mastectomy","Localised excisional biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with screen-detected DCIS confirmed on vacuum-assisted biopsy. The absence of clinical and sonographic abnormalities is common in DCIS, which is often detected only through mammographic microcalcifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocalised excisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E (wide local excision) is the most appropriate next step. The goal is to completely excise the DCIS with clear margins, guided by wire localisation of the mammographic abnormality. This allows definitive histological assessment and ensures complete removal of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly aggressive for a small area of DCIS. It would only be considered for extensive disease, multiple areas of DCIS, or patient preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammographic surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inappropriate as DCIS has the potential to progress to invasive cancer. Once DCIS is diagnosed, surgical excision is indicated to prevent progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECore needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be redundant as the diagnosis has already been established through vacuum-assisted biopsy, which provides larger tissue samples and is particularly useful for sampling microcalcifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETamoxifen\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as adjuvant therapy after surgery in hormone receptor-positive DCIS, but it is not appropriate as primary treatment. Surgical excision remains the standard of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing surgical excision, further treatment decisions (such as radiation therapy or endocrine therapy) will depend on the final pathology results, including margin status, grade, and hormone receptor status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) diagnosed on core biopsy requires surgical excision with clear margins.","Vacuum-assisted biopsy (VAB) showing DCIS requires surgical excision even in the absence of a mass lesion.","Microcalcifications on mammogram may be the only radiological sign of DCIS."],"references":["Kalwaniya DS, Gairola M, Gupta S, Pawan G. Ductal Carcinoma in Situ: A Detailed Review of Current Practices. Cureus. 2023 Apr 21;15(4):e37932. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10200127/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16003"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T09:35:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T14:22:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8694"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86419"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":